  intro="The work I’m doing, the future I’m building toward, the values behind it, and some of the harder conversations that have shaped me."
>
  <section>
    <h2>What I do</h2>
    <p>
      I’m building EzWin Academy, a math tuition business in Singapore. Before
      this, I worked in software and spent years building coding schools and
      education businesses. The common thread has always been the same: take
      something difficult and make it easier for someone else to understand.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What I’m building toward</h2>
    <ul>
      <li data-index="01">
        <strong>A tuition business known for generosity.</strong>
        More useful resources, clearer explanations, and more care than students
        and parents expect to receive.
      </li>
      <li data-index="02">
        <strong>A different kind of physical centre.</strong>
        Laptops instead of stacks of paper, with technology helping teachers see
        exactly where each student is stuck.
      </li>
      <li data-index="03">
        <strong>A life with meaningful ambition.</strong>
        Build something substantial without letting the business become the only
        interesting part of who I am.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What I value</h2>
    <ul>
      <li data-index="01">
        <strong>Over-delivering.</strong>
        Do more than the transaction requires, especially when the extra effort
        helps someone finally understand.
      </li>
      <li data-index="02">
        <strong>Directness with care.</strong>
        Say the true thing early, clearly, and without treating honesty as an
        excuse to be unkind.
      </li>
      <li data-index="03">
        <strong>Building before talking.</strong>
        Ideas become more honest once they meet students, customers, deadlines,
        and the real world.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Hard conversations</h2>
    <p>
      Some of the most important changes in my life started with conversations I
      would rather have avoided: admitting when an idea was not working, telling
      someone what I actually needed, or hearing that my intentions and my impact
      were not the same thing.
    </p>
    <p>
      I’m learning that a difficult conversation is rarely a detour from the
      relationship or the work. Handled properly, it is part of how both become
      real.
    </p>
  </section>
</EditorialPage>
